Most beginner Spring Boot apps start with one class that “just works”: a controller that reads the request, validates it, talks to the database, and returns JSON. It feels fast. Then the app grows, and every change turns into a small risk. That’s the real reason Why Spring Boot Projects Have Controllers, Services, and Repositories keeps coming up in real teams: those three roles create boundaries that stop your codebase from becoming one big, tightly-coupled blob.
This article explains Why Spring Boot Projects Have Controllers, Services, and Repositories using a concrete example: a tiny “create order” flow. We’ll start with the naive version, watch it become fragile, then refactor into something that scales with features and teammates.
Where the pain starts: the “everything controller”
This usually looks harmless at the beginning. One controller method does everything in one place, so you feel productive.
